'''Clarté''' ([[French language|French]] for "clarity") was a [[socialism|socialist]] and [[pacifist]] organisation in [[Norway]].

It was founded in 1925, and had its roots in a French-based international organization of the same name. The international organization became defunct in 1923, but French and Swedish branches existed, and Danish and Finnish branches came in 1925 and 1926.<ref name=pax>{{cite encyclopedia|year=1976 |title=Clarté |last=Hagtvet |first=Bernt |authorlink=Bernt Hagtvet |encyclopedia=[[Pax Leksikon]] |publisher=Pax |location=Oslo |url=http://mediabase1.uib.no/paxlex/alfabetet/c/c04.html#clarte |accessdate=1 January 2010 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120330061459/http://mediabase1.uib.no/paxlex/alfabetet/c/c04.html |archivedate=30 March 2012 |df= }}</ref>

In Norway, Clarté was strongly affiliated with the organization ''[[Mot Dag]]'', and ''Mot Dag''<nowiki>'</nowiki>s [[Arne Ording]] was chairman. Ording also edited the organization's periodical, also named ''Clarté''.<ref name=pax/> This was published between 1929 and 1931.<ref name=snl>{{cite encyclopedia|year=2007|title=Clarté – sosialistiske organisasjoner|encyclopedia=[[Store norske leksikon]]|editor=Henriksen, Petter|publisher=Kunnskapsforlaget|location=Oslo|url=http://www.snl.no/Clart%C3%A9/sosialistiske_organisasjoner|language=Norwegian|accessdate=1 January 2010}}</ref> Another Norwegian, [[Aake Anker Ording]], was secretary-general of ''Nordisk Clartéforbund'' (the Nordic Clarté Association) from 1927.<ref name=pax/> Clarté in Norway existed until 1936, when it was reorganized with the new name Forum.<ref name=snl/> ''Mot Dag'' was disestablished in the same year.<ref>{{cite encyclopedia|year=2007|title=Mot Dag|encyclopedia=[[Store norske leksikon]]|editor=Henriksen, Petter|publisher=Kunnskapsforlaget|location=Oslo|url=http://www.snl.no/Mot_Dag|language=Norwegian|accessdate=1 January 2010}}</ref>

It split in 1940. In light of the [[Winter War]], then-chairman of ''Forum'', [[Gudmund Harlem]], proposed that communists be barred from membership in the organization. 74 voted for, 78 voted against, and the minority left the organization to form ''[[Sosialistisk Studentlag]]''.<ref>{{cite book|last=Pryser|first=Tore|authorlink=Tore Pryser|title=Klassen og nasjonen 1935-1946|year=1988|series=Volume four of ''[[Arbeiderbevegelsens historie i Norge]]''|publisher=Tiden|location=Oslo|language=Norwegian|isbn=82-10-02754-9|pages=229–230}}</ref>

