'''[[Homelessness]] in [[Papua New Guinea]]''' is a significant issue in [[Port Moresby]], the nation's capital city.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hausples.com.pg/news/growth-costs-opportunities-homelessness-papua-new-guinea/|title=Growth, Costs and Opportunities of Homelessness in Papua New Guinea|website=www.hausples.com.pg}}</ref>
==Youth homelessness== It is estimated that the homeless population in the nation's capital includes over 5,000 homeless children. The government and charities working in the region state that migration from rural to urban areas are a leading cause for the rise in homelessness.<ref name=abc1>{{cite web|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2018-03-26/png-government-vows-to-find-shelter-for-port-moresbys-homeless/9587412|title=PNG Government vows to find shelter for Port Moresby's homeless children|date=26 March 2018|website=ABC News}}</ref>
===Working street children=== One study on working [[street children]] in Papua New Guinea surveyed 324 children, of which seven percent were currently living on the street, but overall, 51% had been living on the street at one point in the past.<ref>Kritoe Keleba with Nancy Sullivan. ''Working Street Children of Papua New Guinea''. Department for Community Development, Child Welfare Branch. 2010.</ref>
==Following natural disasters== Other instances of homelessness include families who have lost their homes due to natural disasters. In 2017, around 500 people became homeless following floods in the Eastern Highlands Province.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pireport.org/articles/2017/01/04/500-homeless-pngs-eastern-highlands-province-after-flooding|title=500 Homeless In PNG's Eastern Highlands Province After Flooding - Pacific Islands Report|website=www.pireport.org}}</ref>
In 2007, some 13,000 people became homeless following flooding in the Northern Province.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wsws.org/en/articles/2007/12/png-d06.html|title=Papua New Guinea flood leaves thousands homeless|first=Will|last=Marshall|publisher=}}</ref>
==Government responses== *National Office of Child and Family Service (NOCFS) is tasked with providing a response to homelessness.<ref name=abc1/>
===Legislation=== *''Lukautim Pikinini (Child) Act 2009''<ref name=abc1/>
==Active charities== *Life Care PNG<ref name=abc1/>
